Acidification of the phagosome lumen results from the gradual accumulation of active V-ATPases on the phagosome membrane. This V-ATPase is a multimeric protein complex that translocates protons (H+) into the lumen of the phagosome using cytosolic ATP as an energy source. In order to keep an electrical balance across the phagosome membrane, negative anions (mainly Cl−) also move inside, while cations (such as K+ and Na+) move outside. Phagolysosomes are highly acidic (pH as low as 4.5) thanks to the large number of V-ATPase molecules on their membrane.
